ditor" id="author-1049"><name><surname>Botchan</surname><given-names>Michael R</given-names></name><role>Reviewing editor</role><aff><institution>University of California, Berkeley</institution>, <country>United States</country></aff></contrib></contrib-group><author-notes><corresp id="cor1"><label>*</label>For correspondence: <email>odonnel@mail.rockefeller.edu</email> (MO);</corresp></author-notes><pub-date date-type="pub" publication-format="electronic"><day>04</day><month>09</month><year>2017</year></pub-date><volume>6</volume><elocation-id>e29118</elocation-id><history><date date-type="received"><day>01</day><month>06</month><year>2017</year></date><date date-type="accepted"><day>03</day><month>09</month><year>2017</year></date></history><permissions><copyright-statement>Â© 2017, Langston et al</copyright-statement><copyright-year>2017</copyright-year><copyright-holder>Langston et al</copyright-holder><license xlink:href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"><license-p>This article is distributed under the terms of the <ext-link ext-link-type="uri" xlink:href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">Creative Commons Attribution License</ext-link> permitting unrestricted use and redistribution provided that the original author and source are credited.</license-p></license></permissions><self-uri content-type="pdf" xlink:href="elife-29118-v1.pdf"/><abstract><p>Replicative helicases in all cell types are hexameric rings that unwind DNA by steric exclusion in which the helicase encircles the tracking strand only and excludes the other strand from the ring. This mode of translocation allows helicases to bypass blocks on the strand that is excluded from the central channel. Unlike other replicative helicases, eukaryotic CMG helicase partially encircles duplex DNA at a forked junction and is stopped by a block on the non-tracking (lagging) strand. This report demonstrates that Mcm10, an essential replication protein unique to eukaryotes, binds CMG and greatly stimulates its helicase activity in vitro. Most significantly, Mcm10 enables CMG and the replisome to bypass blocks on the non-tracking DNA strand. We demonstrate that bypass occurs without displacement of the blocks and therefore Mcm10 must isomerize the CMG-DNA complex to achieve the bypass function.</p></abstract><kwd-group kwd-group-type="research-organism"><title>Research organism</title><kwd>S. cerevisiae</kwd></kwd-group><funding-group><award-group id="par-1"><funding-source><institution-wrap><institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100000011</institution-id><institution>Howard Hughes Medical Institute</institution></institution-wrap></funding-source><principal-award-recipient><name><surname>Langston</surname><given-names>Lance D</given-names></name><name><surname>Mayle</surname><given-names>Ryan</given-names></name><name><surname>Yurieva</surname><given-names>Olga</given-names></name><name><surname>Georgescu</surname><given-names>Roxana E</given-names></name><name><surname>O'Donnell</surname><given-names>Mike E</given-names></name></principal-award-recipient></award-group><award-group id="par-2"><funding-source><institution-wrap><institution-id institution-id-type="FundRef">http://dx.doi.org/10.13039/100000002</institution-id><institution>National Institutes of Health</institution></institution-wrap></funding-source><award-id>GM38839</award-id><principal-award-recipient><name><surname>Langston</surname><given-names>Lance D</given-names></name><name><surname>Mayle</surname><given-names>Ryan</given-names></name><name><surname>Schauer</surname><given-names>Grant D</given-names></name><name><surname>Yurieva</surname><given-names>Olga</given-names></name><name><surname>Zhang</surname><given-names>Daniel</given-names></name><name><surname>Yao</surname><given-names>Nina Y</given-names></name><name><surname>Georgescu</surname><given-names>Roxana E</given-names></name><name><surname>O'Donnell</surname><given-names>Mike E</given-na